Since 64 = 2^6, every factor in a multiplicative partition of 64 must be a power of 2, say 2^{t_i} with t_i ≥ 1. A product of such factors equals 2^{t_1 + t_2 + ... + t_k} = 2^6, so t_1 + t_2 + ... + t_k = 6 with each t_i ≥ 1. The order of factors is irrelevant, so each multiplicative partition of 64 corresponds uniquely to a partition of the integer 6.

Therefore P(64) = p(6), the number of partitions of 6. Since p(6) = 11, we have

\boxed{11}
